com.inqwell.any

Class AnyQueue

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.inqwell.any.AbstractComposite
      • com.inqwell.any.AnyQueue
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Any, Array, Composite, Orderable, Queue, Vectored, Serializable, Cloneable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    NodeSpecification

    public class AnyQueue
extends AbstractComposite
implements Queue, Vectored, Orderable, Cloneable
    Concrete Queue composite. Such composites can operate as LIFOs or FIFOs. The access methods by index are relatively inefficient as compared to arrays since the implementation is a LinkedList
    See Also:

      • sort

        public void sort(Array orderBy)
        Description copied from interface: Orderable
        Reorder this Orderable's immediate children. The contents of the collection will be reordered according to the natural ordering of the element contents. This method uses the AnyComparator implementation to do the ordering.

        Any previously held comparator within the Orderable implementation is diacarded and this instance is then no longer capable of intrinsic reordering or maintaining correct the correct order as new nodes are added.

        Specified by:
        sort in interface Orderable
        Parameters:
        orderBy - an array of NodeSpecification objects which locate the desired elements under the this array defining the order criteria.

      • sort

        public void sort(OrderComparator c)
        Description copied from interface: Orderable
        Reorder this Orderable's immediate children. The contents of the collection will be reordered according to the given comparator implementation.

        Implementations are at liberty to remember the OrderComparator that they are passed for future reordering and for maintaining the current order as new elements are inserted into them. Clients should arrange to clone the comparator to avoid problems of inadvertant object sharing.

        Specified by:
        sort in interface Orderable

        Implementations are at liberty to remember the OrderComparator that they are passed for future reordering and for maintaining the current order as new elements are inserted into them. Clients should arrange to clone the comparator to avoid problems of inadvertant object sharing.

      • addByVector

        public void addByVector(int at,
                        Any value)
        Description copied from interface: Vectored
        Places the given value at the specified location in the collection. If the location is not in the range 0 to entries() then an exception is generated unless the collection can be sparse. If setSparse(true) has previously been called then place-holders are inserted as required.

        If the implementation is a map then a suitable key will be invented for the value, for example its identity.

        Specified by:
        addByVector in interface Vectored
